### What is the difference between Entra Private Access and Quick Access in Microsoft Entra?

In Microsoft Entra Global Secure Access, **Entra Private Access** and **Quick Access** are both components that enable secure access to private resources, but they differ in their approach and scope. 

**Entra Private Access** is a more comprehensive, Zero Trust Network Access (ZTNA) solution that replaces traditional VPNs by providing per-app, granular access to private resources based on user identity and device posture. 

**Quick Access**, on the other hand, is a simplified configuration within Private Access that allows you to define specific fully qualified domain names (FQDNs) and IP addresses for your private apps and resources, enabling traffic forwarding to the service. Quick Access is not a separate product but rather a specific configuration within the Entra Private Access service.

| Entra Private Access | Entra Private Quick Access |
| ----- | ----- |
| **Zero Trust Approach**: It's built on the principles of Zero Trust, meaning it assumes no user or device can be trusted by default and requires verification at each access attempt.  | **Simplified Configuration:** It provides a streamlined way to configure traffic forwarding for specific private resources within Private Access. |
| **Per-app, Granular Access**: It allows you to define specific applications and resources within your private network that users can access, rather than granting broad network access like a VPN.  | **Traffic Forwarding Profile:** You define the FQDNs and IP addresses of the private apps and resources you want to route through the service in a traffic forwarding profile. |
| **Enhanced Security:** It minimises the attack surface by only allowing access to authorised resources and enforcing security policies through Conditional Access.   | **Enhanced Security:** Conditional Access**?** |
| **Modernised Access:** It replaces traditional VPNs with a more secure and efficient solution for accessing private resources.  | **Transition Phase:** It can be used as a transition phase in your Zero Trust journey, allowing you **to replace your VPN with Private Access gradually**. |
| **Requires Global Secure Access client:** To use Entra Private Access, the Global Secure Access client must be installed on end-user devices. | **Client Required:** Just like Entra Private Access, Quick Access also requires the Global Secure Access client to be installed on end-user devices.  |

**Why use restricted management administrative units?** 

Here are some reasons why you might use restricted management administrative units to help manage access in your tenant.

* Protect your executive accounts and their devices

You want to protect your C-level executive accounts and their devices **from Helpdesk Administrators who would otherwise be able to reset their passwords** **or access BitLocker recovery keys**. You can add your C-level user accounts to a **restricted management administrative unit and enable a specific trusted set of administrators who can reset their passwords and access BitLocker recovery keys** when needed.

* Implement compliance control for only local administrators

You want to implement a compliance control **to ensure that certain resources can only be managed by administrators in a specific country/region.** You can add those resources to a restricted management administrative unit and assign local administrators to manage those objects. **Even Global Administrators won't be allowed to modify the objects unless they assign themselves explicitly to a role scoped to the restricted management administrative unit (which is an auditable event)**.

* Restrict management of sensitive security groups to specific administrators

You**'re using security groups to control access to sensitive applications in your organisation**, and you **don't want to allow your tenant-scoped administrators who can modify groups** to be able to control who can access the applications. You can add those security groups to a restricted management administrative unit and then be sure that only the specific administrators you assign can manage them.

# [Priva Privacy Risk Management](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/privacy/priva/risk-management) 

[Informationen zum Datenschutz-Risikomanagement](https://learn.microsoft.com/de-de/privacy/priva/risk-management)

It gives you the capability to set up policies that identify privacy risks in your Microsoft 365 environment and enable easy remediation.

Key targets that are reached **by setting up a Priva Privacy Risk Management Policy**:

* Detect overexposed personal data so that users can secure it.  
    
* Spot and limit transfers of personal data:  
    
  *  across departments   
  * regional borders  
  * Internal and external users


* Help users identify and reduce the amount of unused personal data that you store, i.e. with GDPR, it can help to identify historical data of customers that is no longer in use and should be removed.
